Linux/UNIX is a powerful operating system with a wide range of commands that allow users to interact with the system and 
perform various tasks. Here are some of the basic commands that you should be familiar with:

ls: Lists the files and directories in the current directory.

Usage: ls [options] [path]
cd: Changes the current directory to the specified directory.

Usage: cd [path]
pwd: Prints the current working directory.

Usage: pwd
mkdir: Creates a new directory with the specified name.

Usage: mkdir [directory_name]
rm: Deletes a file or directory.

Usage: rm [options] [file_or_directory]
cp: Copies a file from one location to another.

Usage: cp [options] [source_file] [destination_file]
mv: Moves a file from one location to another or renames a file.

Usage: mv [options] [source_file] [destination_file]
cat: Concatenates files and prints the output to the console.

Usage: cat [options] [file]
grep: Searches for a pattern in a file or directory.

Usage: grep [options] [pattern] [file_or_directory]
echo: Prints the specified message to the console.

Usage: echo [message]

ps: Lists the running processes on the system.
Usage: ps [options]

kill: Sends a signal to a process to terminate it.
Usage: kill [options] [process_id]

chmod: Changes the permissions of a file or directory.
Usage: chmod [options] [permissions] [file_or_directory]

tar: Compresses or archives files and directories.
Usage: tar [options] [archive_name] [file_or_directory]

ssh: Connects to a remote server over a secure shell connection.
Usage: ssh [options] [username]@[hostname]

These are just a few of the many commands available in Linux
/UNIX. With practice, you'll become more familiar with these commands and their options, 
and you'll be able to perform more complex tasks on your system.